<http://status.aws.amazon.com/|Informational message: Increased Launch Error Rates>
We are investigating increased error rates for new launches of C5 and M5 instance types in a single Availability Zone in the US-WEST-2 Region.

<http://status.aws.amazon.com/|Informational message: Increased Launch Error Rates>
We can confirm increased error rates for new launches of C5 and M5 instance types in a single Availability Zone in the US-WEST-2 Region. We have identified the root cause and are working toward full resolution. In the interim, we recommend customers launch their instances to an alternate Availability Zone.

<http://status.aws.amazon.com/|Service is operating normally: [RESOLVED] Increased Launch Error Rates>
We have resolved the issue affecting new launches of C5 and M5 instance types in a single Availability Zone in the US-WEST-2 Region. Existing instances were not affected. The issue has been resolved and the service is operating normally.

<http://status.aws.amazon.com/|Informational message: Elevated DNS Resolution Errors>
Between 2:41 and 2:56 PM PST some EC2 instances experienced elevated DNS resolution errors in the EU-WEST-1 Region. As a result of this, some AWS services experienced elevated errors and increased latency. The issue has been resolved and the service is operating normally.

<http://status.aws.amazon.com/|Informational message: Elevated DNS Resolution Errors>
Between 2:41 and 2:56 PM PST some EC2 instances experienced elevated DNS resolution errors in the EU-CENTRAL-1 Region. As a result of this, some AWS services experienced elevated errors and increased latency. The issue has been resolved and the service is operating normally.
